olored urine. Therapy should be discontinued if creatine kinase is markedly elevated in the absence of strenuous exercise or if myopathy is otherwise suspected or diagnosed.', 'Metabolism', 'Cholestyramine, Rosuvastatin, Fenofibrate, Mipomersen, Evinacumab, Dextrothyroxine, Probucol, Ezetimibe, Niacin, Colesevelam, Fluvastatin, More', 'Lamivudine, Paritaprevir, Tenofovir alafenamide, Maraviroc, Cabotegravir, Zanamivir, Rilpivirine, Dolutegravir, Brincidofovir, Elbasvir, Famciclovir, More', 'Major', NULL, 'DDInter', 'pharmacodynamic', NULL, 'https://ddinter2.scbdd.com/server/interact/133090/', '[1] Lee AJ, Maddix DS "Rhabdomyolysis secondary to a drug interaction between simvastatin and clarithromycin." Ann Pharmacother 35 (2001): 26-31[2] Dresser GK, Spence JD, Bailey DG "Pharmacokinetic-pharmacodynamic consequences and clinical relevance of cytochrome P450 3A4 inhibition." Clin Pharmacokinet 38 (2000): 41-57[3] Spach DH, Bauwens JE, Clark CD, Burke WG "Rhabdomyolysis associated with lovastatin and erythromycin use." West J Med 154 (1991): 213-5[4] Omar MA, Wilson JP "FDA adverse event reports on statin-associated rhabdomyolysis." Ann Pharmacother 36 (2002): 288-95[5] Jody DN "Myositis and rhabdomyolysis associated with concurrent use of simvastatin and nefazodone." JAMA 277 (1997): 296-7[6] Piliero PJ "Interaction between ritonavir and statins." Am J Med 112 (2002): 510-1[7] Fichtenbaum CJ, Gerber JG, Rosenkranz SL, et al. "Pharmacokinetic interactions between protease inhibitors and statins in HIV seronegative volunteers: ACTG Study A5047." AIDS 16 (2002): 569-577[8] Thompson M, Samuels S "Rhabdomyolysis with simvastatin and nefazodone." Am J Psychiatry 159 (2002): 1607[9] East C, Alivizatos PA, Grundy SM, Jones PH, Farmer JA "Rhabdomyolysis in patients receiving lovastatin after cardiac transplantation." N Engl J Med 318 (1988): 47-8[10] Wong PW, Dillard TA, Kroenke K "Multiple organ toxicity from addition of erythromycin to long-term lovastatin therapy." South M